{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538812"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:32:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16351"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16351"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.25,0.49,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9042"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64850"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9042"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16351"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50284"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4089"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4832"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43628"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64850"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with a six-month history of progressively worsening heavy menstrual bleeding. She reports flooding through pads and clots. Her periods occur every 28 days and last for seven days. She has no intermenstrual or post-coital bleeding. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has two children, both delivered vaginally, and uses barrier contraception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m2. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Speculum examination reveals a normal cervix. A cervical co-test is performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound reveals a 12 mm x 8mm focal area of increased echogenicity within the endometrial cavity. The remainder of the endometrium measures 4 mm in thickness. Her haemoglobin is 112 g/L (115-160). Endometrial pipelle reveals proliferative endometrium only.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hysterectomy","Tranexamic acid","Levonorgestrel intrauterine system","Hysteroscopy with polypectomy","Combined oral contraceptive pill"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding and ultrasound findings suggestive of a focal endometrial abnormality, most likely representing an endometrial polyp. The normal pipelle biopsy result cannot exclude focal pathology as blind sampling techniques frequently miss focal lesions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysteroscopy with polypectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation for focal endometrial abnormalities. It allows direct visualisation of the endometrial cavity and targeted biopsy of suspicious areas. This approach provides both diagnostic certainty and the opportunity for concurrent treatment through polypectomy if a polyp is identified. Given the patient\u0027s age and symptoms, tissue diagnosis is essential to exclude endometrial hyperplasia or malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E and other medical treatments may reduce menstrual blood loss but do not address the underlying focal abnormality which requires investigation. Medical management alone is inappropriate when there is a structural abnormality requiring tissue diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elevonorgestrel intrauterine system\u003C/strong\u003E would be an excellent option for managing heavy menstrual bleeding once the focal abnormality has been investigated and treated. However, insertion may be technically difficult or contraindicated in the presence of an endometrial polyp.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E can help regulate menstrual bleeding but, like other medical treatments, does not address the focal endometrial abnormality which requires investigation and possible removal. Caution should also be used in considered COCP and risk for DVT in women \u0026gt;35 years. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHysterectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overly aggressive approach without first attempting conservative investigation and management. While it may ultimately be required if conservative measures fail, it would be inappropriate as a first-line treatment without investigating the focal abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hysteroscopy with directed biopsy is the gold standard for investigating focal endometrial abnormalities identified on ultrasound.","Blind endometrial sampling may miss focal lesions such as polyps.","Women with heavy menstrual bleeding and focal endometrial abnormalities require tissue diagnosis to exclude malignancy."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Heavy Menstrual Bleeding: Clinical Practice Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 24]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Heavy-Menstrual-Bleeding.pdf","Sheng KK, Lyons SD. To treat or not to treat? An evidence-based practice guide for the management of endometrial polyps. Climacteric. 2020 Aug;23(4):336-342. doi: 10.1080/13697137.2020.1742107. Epub 2020 Jun 4. PMID: 32496825.","Vitale SG, Haimovich S, Lagan\u00e0 AS, Alonso L, Di Spiezio Sardo A, Carugno J; From the Global Community of Hysteroscopy Guidelines Committee. Endometrial polyps. An evidence-based diagnosis and management guide. Eur J Obstet Gynecol Reprod Biol. 2021 May;260:70-77. doi: 10.1016/j.ejogrb.2021.03.017. Epub 2021 Mar 13. PMID: 33756339."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50284"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16351"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50284"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T18:51:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T18:52:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9042"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64850"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the